ce:section.ce:para:
To investigate the photothermal and chemo-photothermal effect of the prepared nanocarriers, the MCF-10 as a breast normal cell line and MCF-7, MDA-MB-231, and SKBR-3 as breast cancer cell lines were irradiated with 1 W/ cm2 NIR laser for 10 min at a specific time point during the incubation with CQD, free Dox, niosome-FA, TS-Nio-FA, Dox @ niosome-FA, Dox @ TS-Nio-FA, CQD & Dox @ niosome-FA, and CQD & Dox @ TS-Nio-FA. The results showed (Fig. 9
                        ) that the CQDs as an effective photothermal agent, could destroy the cells, but like anti-cancer drugs in chemotherapy (the second column in each group), they cannot distinguish between normal and cancer cells. In contrast, 10 min NIR laser irradiation has an insignificant effect on cell viability in all cell types studied in high glucose DMEM medium without CQDs as blank, which indicates that the photothermal effect is observed only in the presence of the CQDs. The combination of released drug treatment with NIR irradiation (chemo-photothermal therapy) can destroyed the tumor cells in two cases more effectively in comparison with the Dox loaded in formulations (chemotherapy) and NIR laser irradiation in the presence of CQDs (photothermal therapy). The normal cell line and SKBR-3 were resistant to the chemo-photothermal therapy. According to the results, CQD & Dox @ TS-Nio-FA could kill the cancer cells even more than the CQDs & Dox @ niosome-FA and it can be caused by the effect of high temperature on the percentages of drug released. The combination of chemotherapy and photothermal therapy toward MCF-7, MDA-MB-231, and SKBR-3 cells was evaluated by combination index (CI) analysis. It was calculated using the reported equation in previous studies [69,70]. The value of CI can be used to classify treatment interactions as antagonistic (CI greater than 1), additive (CI = 1), and synergistic (CI less than 1). The IC50 value of each treatment and calculated CI for cancer cells are exhibited in Table 4
                        . The presented data showed a significant decrease in IC50 in combined therapy for MCF-7 and MDA-MB-231 cells, and the calculated CI values were 0.52 and 0.49, respectively. These values indicate the synergistic effect of chemotherapy and photothermal therapy. On the contrary, in SKBR-3 cells, The IC50 value of combined therapy was increased, and the calculated CI was about 1.5, which indicates an antagonistic effect. The synergistic effect in MCF-7 and MDA-MB-231 cells was probably ascribed to enhanced Dox release via NIR-triggered manner, increased intracellular drug delivery, and cell death via NIR laser irradiation.
